 is reinforced through two parallel labels (“BIOMOLECULES” and “BIO MOLECULES”)\",\"explanation\":\"Two entities—“BIOMOLECULES” and “BIO MOLECULES”—both describe the main substances forming living matter/living body and list carbohydrates among the primary types. This suggests either duplication across sources or intentional reinforcement of key categories using variant labeling. [Data: Entities (217, 489, 218); Relationships (176, 529)]\\n\\nThe descriptions also situate carbohydrates within a broader set that includes proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids (with vitamins noted as organic compounds found in living matter), indicating that carbohydrate content is part of a larger comparative framework of biological macromolecules and related compounds. [Data: Entities (217, 489, 135, 132)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Food examples (potato, sweet potato, flour) operationalize carbohydrate concepts for learners\",\"explanation\":\"Potato, sweet potato, and flour are each explicitly connected as examples of carbohydrate-containing foods. These relationships show a pedagogical bridge from biochemical definition to everyday dietary sources, likely aimed at recognition and application. [Data: Entities (226, 227, 230, 218); Relationships (237, 238, 241)]\\n\\nFlour additionally appears as a required material in a laboratory/food context tied to an amylase-on-starch activity, implying hands-on experimentation to demonstrate carbohydrate breakdown or identification. [Data: Entities (230, 218)]\"},{\"summary\":\"The community includes laboratory-identification framing for carbohydrates (tests for starch, monosaccharides, disaccharides)\",\"explanation\":\"Beyond definitions and examples, the carbohydrate entity notes that laboratory tests can be used to identify different types of carbohydrates, specifically mentioning tests for starch, monosaccharides, and disaccharides. This indicates an applied technical component (basic lab methods) embedded within the educational content. [Data: Enti